# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: selenocysteine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] In molecular genetics, the **three prime untranslated region** (**3′ UTR**) is the section of messenger RNA (mRNA) that immediately follows the translation termination codon.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] The 3′ UTR often contains regulatory regions that post-transcriptionally influence gene expression.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] During gene expression, an mRNA molecule is transcribed from the DNA sequence and is later translated into a protein.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Several regions of the mRNA molecule are not translated into a protein including the 5′ cap, 5′ untranslated region, 3′ untranslated region and poly(A) tail.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Regulatory regions within the 3′ untranslated region can influence polyadenylation, translation efficiency, localization, and stability of the mRNA.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] The 3′ UTR contains binding sites for both regulatory proteins and microRNAs (miRNAs).
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] By binding to specific sites within the 3′ UTR, miRNAs can decrease gene expression of various mRNAs by either inhibiting translation or directly causing degradation of the transcript.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] The 3′ UTR also has silencer regions which bind to repressor proteins and will inhibit the expression of the mRNA.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Many 3′ UTRs also contain AU-rich elements (AREs).
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Proteins bind AREs to affect the stability or decay rate of transcripts in a localized manner or affect translation initiation.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Furthermore, the 3′ UTR contains the sequence AAUAAA that directs addition of several hundred adenine residues called the poly(A) tail to the end of the mRNA transcript.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Poly(A) binding protein (PABP) binds to this tail, contributing to regulation of mRNA translation, stability, and export.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] For example, poly(A) tail bound PABP interacts with proteins associated with the 5′ end of the transcript, causing a circularization of the mRNA that promotes translation.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] The 3′ UTR can also contain sequences that attract proteins to associate the mRNA with the cytoskeleton, transport it to or from the cell nucleus, or perform other types of localization.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] In addition to sequences within the 3′ UTR, the physical characteristics of the region, including its length and secondary structure, contribute to translation regulation.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] These diverse mechanisms of gene regulation ensure that the correct genes are expressed in the correct cells at the appropriate times.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] The 3′ UTR of mRNA has a great variety of regulatory functions that are controlled by the physical characteristics of the region.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] One such characteristic is the length of the 3′ UTR, which in the mammalian genome has considerable variation.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] This region of the mRNA transcript can range from 60 nucleotides to about 4000.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] On average the length for the 3′ UTR in humans is approximately 800 nucleotides, while the average length of 5′ UTRs is only about 200 nucleotides.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] The length of the 3′ UTR is significant since longer 3′ UTRs are associated with lower levels of gene expression.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] One possible explanation for this phenomenon is that longer regions have a higher probability of possessing more miRNA binding sites that have the ability to inhibit translation.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] In addition to length, the nucleotide composition also differs significantly between the 5′ and the 3′ UTR.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] The mean G+C percentage of the 5′ UTR in warm-blooded vertebrates is about 60% as compared to only 45% for 3′ UTRs.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] This is important because an inverse correlation has been observed between the G+C% of 5′ and 3′ UTRs and their corresponding lengths.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] The UTRs that are GC-poor tend to be longer than those located in GC-rich genomic regions.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Sequences within the 3′ UTR also have the ability to degrade or stabilize the mRNA transcript.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Modifications that control a transcript's stability allow expression of a gene to be rapidly controlled without altering translation rates.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] One group of elements in the 3′ UTR that can help destabilize an mRNA transcript are the AU-rich elements (AREs).
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] These elements range in size from 50 to 150 base pairs and generally contain multiple copies of the pentanucleotide AUUUA.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Early studies indicated that AREs can vary in sequence and fall into three main classes that differ in the number and arrangement of motifs.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Another set of elements that is present in both the 5′ and the 3′ UTR are iron response elements (IREs).
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] The IRE is a stem-loop structure within the untranslated regions of mRNAs that encode proteins involved in cellular iron metabolism.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] The mRNA transcript containing this element is either degraded or stabilized depending upon the binding of specific proteins and the intracellular iron concentrations.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] The 3′ UTR also contains sequences that signal additions to be made, either to the transcript itself or to the product of translation.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] For example, there are two different polyadenylation signals present within the 3′ UTR that signal the addition of the poly(A) tail.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] These signals initiate the synthesis of the poly(A) tail at a defined length of about 250 base pairs.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] The primary signal used is the nuclear polyadenylation signal (PAS) with the sequence AAUAAA located toward the end of the 3′ UTR.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] However, during early development cytoplasmic polyadenylation can occur instead and regulate the translational activation of maternal mRNAs.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] The element that controls this process is called the CPE which is AU-rich and located in the 3′ UTR as well.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] The CPE generally has the structure UUUUUUAU and is usually within 100 base pairs of the nuclear PAS.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Another specific addition signaled by the 3′ UTR is the incorporation of selenocysteine at UGA codons of mRNAs encoding selenoproteins.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Normally the UGA codon encodes for a stop of translation, but in this case a conserved stem-loop structure called the selenocysteine insertion sequence (SECIS) causes for the insertion of selenocysteine instead.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] The 3′ untranslated region plays a crucial role in gene expression by influencing the localization, stability, export, and translation efficiency of an mRNA.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] It contains various sequences that are involved in gene expression, including microRNA response elements (MREs), AU-rich elements (AREs), and the poly(A) tail.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] In addition, the structural characteristics of the 3′ UTR as well as its use of alternative polyadenylation play a role in gene expression.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] The 3′ UTR often contains microRNA response elements (MREs), which are sequences to which miRNAs bind. miRNAs are short, non-coding RNA molecules capable of binding to mRNA transcripts and regulating their expression.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] One miRNA mechanism involves partial base pairing of the 5′ seed sequence of an miRNA to an MRE within the 3′ UTR of an mRNA; this binding then causes translational repression.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] In addition to containing MREs, the 3′ UTR also often contains AU-rich elements (AREs), which are 50 to 150 bp in length and usually include many copies of the sequence AUUUA.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] ARE binding proteins (ARE-BPs) bind to AU-rich elements in a manner that is dependent upon tissue type, cell type, timing, cellular localization, and environment.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] In response to different intracellular and extracellular signals, ARE-BPs can promote mRNA decay, affect mRNA stability, or activate translation.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] This mechanism of gene regulation is involved in cell growth, cellular differentiation, and adaptation to external stimuli.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] It therefore acts on transcripts encoding cytokines, growth factors, tumor suppressors, proto-oncogenes, cyclins, enzymes, transcription factors, receptors, and membrane proteins.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] The poly(A) tail contains binding sites for poly(A) binding proteins (PABPs).
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] These proteins cooperate with other factors to affect the export, stability, decay, and translation of an mRNA.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] PABPs bound to the poly(A) tail may also interact with proteins, such as translation initiation factors, that are bound to the 5′ cap of the mRNA.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] This interaction causes circularization of the transcript, which subsequently promotes translation initiation.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Furthermore, it allows for efficient translation by causing recycling of ribosomes.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] While the presence of a poly(A) tail usually aids in triggering translation, the absence or removal of one often leads to exonuclease-mediated degradation of the mRNA.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Polyadenylation itself is regulated by sequences within the 3′ UTR of the transcript.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] These sequences include cytoplasmic polyadenylation elements (CPEs), which are uridine-rich sequences that contribute to both polyadenylation activation and repression.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] CPE-binding protein (CPEB) binds to CPEs in conjunction with a variety of other proteins in order to elicit different responses.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] While the sequence that constitutes the 3′ UTR contributes greatly to gene expression, the structural characteristics of the 3′ UTR also play a large role.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] In general, longer 3′ UTRs correspond to lower expression rates since they often contain more miRNA and protein binding sites that are involved in inhibiting translation.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Human transcripts possess 3′ UTRs that are on average twice as long as other mammalian 3′ UTRs.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] This trend reflects the high level of complexity involved in human gene regulation.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] In addition to length, the secondary structure of the 3′ untranslated region also has regulatory functions.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Protein factors can either aid or disrupt folding of the region into various secondary structures.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] The most common structure is a stem-loop, which provides a scaffold for RNA binding proteins and non-coding RNAs that influence expression of the transcript.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Another mechanism involving the structure of the 3′ UTR is called alternative polyadenylation (APA), which results in mRNA isoforms that differ only in their 3′ UTRs.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] This mechanism is especially useful for complex organisms as it provides a means of expressing the same protein but in varying amounts and locations.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] It is utilized by about half of human genes.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] APA can result from the presence of multiple polyadenylation sites or mutually exclusive terminal exons.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Since it can affect the presence of protein and miRNA binding sites, APA can cause differential expression of mRNA transcripts by influencing their stability, export to the cytoplasm, and translation efficiency.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Scientists use a number of methods to study the complex structures and functions of the 3′ UTR.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Even if a given 3′ UTR in an mRNA is shown to be present in a tissue, the effects of localization, functional half-life, translational efficiency, and trans-acting elements must be determined to understand the 3′ UTR's full functionality.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Computational approaches, primarily by sequence analysis, have shown the existence of AREs in approximately 5 to 8% of human 3′ UTRs and the presence of one or more miRNA targets in as many as 60% or more of human 3′ UTRs.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Software can rapidly compare millions of sequences at once to find similarities between various 3′ UTRs within the genome.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Experimental approaches have been used to define sequences that associate with specific RNA-binding proteins; specifically, recent improvements in sequencing and cross-linking techniques have enabled fine mapping of protein binding sites within the transcript.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Induced site-specific mutations, for example those that affect the termination codon, polyadenylation signal, or secondary structure of the 3′ UTR, can show how mutated regions can cause translation deregulation and disease.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] These types of transcript-wide methods should help our understanding of known cis elements and trans-regulatory factors within 3′ UTRs.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] 3′ UTR mutations can be very consequential because one alteration can be responsible for the altered expression of many genes.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Transcriptionally, a mutation may affect only the allele and genes that are physically linked.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] However, since 3′ UTR binding proteins also function in the processing and nuclear export of mRNA, a mutation can also affect other unrelated genes.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Dysregulation of ARE-binding proteins (AUBPs) due to mutations in AU-rich regions can lead to diseases including tumorigenesis (cancer), hematopoietic malignancies, leukemogenesis, and developmental delay/autism spectrum disorders.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] An expanded number of trinucleotide (CTG) repeats in the 3′ UTR of the dystrophia myotonica protein kinase (DMPK) gene causes myotonic dystrophy.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Retro-transposal 3-kilobase insertion of tandem repeat sequences within the 3′ UTR of fukutin protein is linked to Fukuyama-type congenital muscular dystrophy.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Elements in the 3′ UTR have also been linked to human acute myeloid leukemia, alpha-thalassemia, neuroblastoma, Keratinopathy, Aniridia, IPEX syndrome, and congenital heart defects.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] The few UTR-mediated diseases identified only hint at the countless links yet to be discovered.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Despite current understanding of 3′ UTRs, they are still relative mysteries.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Since mRNAs usually contain several overlapping control elements, it is often difficult to specify the identity and function of each 3′ UTR element, let alone the regulatory factors that may bind at these sites.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Additionally, each 3′ UTR contains many alternative AU-rich elements and polyadenylation signals.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] These cis- and trans-acting elements, along with miRNAs, offer a virtually limitless range of control possibilities within a single mRNA.
[src:selenocysteine/3-utr] Future research through the increased use of deep-sequencing based ribosome profiling will reveal more regulatory subtleties as well as new control elements and AUBPs.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In chemistry, an **acid dissociation constant** (also known as **acidity constant**, or **acid-ionization constant**; denoted ⁠ $K_{a}$ ⁠) is a quantitative measure of the strength of an acid in solution.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] known as dissociation in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The chemical species HA is an acid that dissociates into A−, called the conjugate base of the acid, and a hydrogen ion, H+.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The system is said to be in equilibrium when the concentrations of its components do not change over time, because both forward and backward reactions are occurring at the same rate.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where quantities in square brackets represent the molar concentrations of the species at equilibrium.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, a hypothetical weak acid having *K*a = 10−5, the value of log *K*a is the exponent (−5), giving p*K*a = 5.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A lower *K*a corresponds to a weaker acid (an acid that is less dissociated at equilibrium).
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The form p*K*a is often used because it provides a convenient logarithmic scale, and a lower p*K*a corresponds to a stronger acid.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The acid dissociation constant for an acid is a direct consequence of the underlying thermodynamics of the dissociation reaction; the p*K*a value is directly proportional to the standard Gibbs free energy change for the reaction.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The value of the p*K*a changes with temperature and can be understood qualitatively based on Le Chatelier's principle: when the reaction is endothermic, *K*a increases and p*K*a decreases with increasing temperature; the opposite is true for exothermic reactions.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The value of p*K*a also depends on molecular structure of the acid in many ways.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, Linus Pauling proposed two rules: one for successive p*K*a of polyprotic acids (see Polyprotic acids below), and one to estimate the p*K*a of oxyacids based on the number of =O and −OH groups (see Factors that affect p*K*a values below).
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other structural factors that influence the magnitude of the acid dissociation constant include inductive effects, mesomeric effects, and hydrogen bonding.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Hammett type equations have frequently been applied to the estimation of p*K*a.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The quantitative behaviour of acids and bases in solution can be understood only if their p*K*a values are known.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In particular, the pH of a solution can be predicted when the analytical concentration and p*K*a values of all acids and bases are known; conversely, it is possible to calculate the equilibrium concentration of the acids and bases in solution when the pH is known.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These calculations find application in many different areas of chemistry, biology, medicine, and geology.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, many compounds used for medication are weak acids or bases, and a knowledge of the p*K*a values, together with the octanol-water partition coefficient, can be used for estimating the extent to which the compound enters the blood stream.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acid dissociation constants are also essential in aquatic chemistry and chemical oceanography, where the acidity of water plays a fundamental role.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In living organisms, acid–base homeostasis and enzyme kinetics are dependent on the p*K*a values of the many acids and bases present in the cell and in the body.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In chemistry, a knowledge of p*K*a values is necessary for the preparation of buffer solutions and is also a prerequisite for a quantitative understanding of the interaction between acids or bases and metal ions to form complexes.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Experimentally, p*K*a values can be determined by potentiometric (pH) titration, but for values of p*K*a less than about 2 or more than about 11, spectrophotometric or NMR measurements may be required due to practical difficulties with pH measurements.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The equilibrium constant for this dissociation reaction is known as a dissociation constant.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The acid loses a proton, leaving a conjugate base; the proton is transferred to the base, creating a conjugate acid.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For aqueous solutions of an acid HA, the base is water; the conjugate base is A− and the conjugate acid is the hydronium ion.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The Brønsted–Lowry definition applies to other solvents, such as dimethyl sulfoxide: the solvent S acts as a base, accepting a proton and forming the conjugate acid SH+.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In solution chemistry, it is common to use H+ as an abbreviation for the solvated hydrogen ion, regardless of the solvent.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aqueous solution H+ denotes a solvated hydronium ion rather than a proton.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The designation of an acid or base as "conjugate" depends on the context.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The hydroxide ion OH−, a well known base, is here acting as the conjugate base of the acid water.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acids and bases are thus regarded simply as donors and acceptors of protons respectively.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A broader definition of acid dissociation includes hydrolysis, in which protons are produced by the splitting of water molecules.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] According to Lewis's original definition, an acid is a substance that accepts an electron pair to form a coordinate covalent bond.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid dissociation constant is a particular example of an equilibrium constant.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where $\{X\}$ represents the activity, at equilibrium, of the chemical species X. $K^{\ominus }$ is dimensionless since activity is dimensionless.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Activities of the products of dissociation are placed in the numerator, activities of the reactants are placed in the denominator.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] See activity coefficient for a derivation of this expression.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where $[{\text{HA}}]$ represents the concentration of HA and ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠ is a quotient of activity coefficients.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To avoid the complications involved in using activities, dissociation constants are determined, where possible, in a medium of high ionic strength, that is, under conditions in which ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠ can be assumed to be always constant.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the medium might be a solution of 0.1 molar (M) sodium nitrate or 3 M potassium perchlorate.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note, however, that all published dissociation constant values refer to the specific ionic medium used in their determination and that different values are obtained with different conditions, as shown for acetic acid in the illustration above.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When published constants refer to an ionic strength other than the one required for a particular application, they may be adjusted by means of specific ion theory (SIT) and other theories.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note that in the context of metal-ligand complex formation, the equilibrium constants for the formation of metal complexes are usually defined as *association* constants.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In that case, the equilibrium constants for ligand protonation are also defined as association constants.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When discussing the properties of acids it is usual to specify equilibrium constants as acid dissociation constants, denoted by *K*a, with numerical values given the symbol p*K*a.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] On the other hand, association constants are used for bases.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] However, general purpose computer programs that are used to derive equilibrium constant values from experimental data use association constants for both acids and bases.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Because stability constants for a metal-ligand complex are always specified as association constants, ligand protonation must also be specified as an association reaction.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The association constant for the formation of a supramolecular complex may be denoted as Ka; in such cases "a" stands for "association", not "acid".
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For polyprotic acids, the numbering of stepwise association constants is the reverse of the numbering of the dissociation constants.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] ⁠ R ⁠ is the gas constant and ⁠ T ⁠ is the absolute temperature.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Thus, for exothermic reactions, the standard enthalpy change, ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠, is negative and *K* decreases with temperature.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For endothermic reactions, ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠ is positive and *K* increases with temperature.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where ⁠ $\Delta C_{p}$ ⁠ is the heat capacity change at constant pressure.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In practice ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠ may be taken to be constant over a small temperature range.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Express each concentration value as the ratio c/c0, where c0 is the concentration in a [hypothetical] standard state, with a numerical value of 1, by definition.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Express the concentrations on the mole fraction scale.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Since mole fraction has no dimension, the quotient of concentrations will, by definition, be a pure number.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The first and second options above give identical numerical values for an equilibrium constant.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is common practice in biochemistry to quote a value with a dimension as, for example, "*K*a = 30 mM" in order to indicate the scale, millimolar (mM) or micromolar (μM) of the concentration values used for its calculation.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid is classified as "strong" when the concentration of its undissociated species is too low to be measured.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Any aqueous acid with a p*K*a value of less than 0 is almost completely deprotonated and is considered a *strong acid*.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] All such acids transfer their protons to water and form the solvent cation species (H3O+ in aqueous solution) so that they all have essentially the same acidity, a phenomenon known as solvent leveling.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] They are said to be *fully dissociated* in aqueous solution because the amount of undissociated acid, in equilibrium with the dissociation products, is below the detection limit.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Likewise, any aqueous base with an association constant p*K*b less than about 0, corresponding to p*K*a greater than about 14, is leveled to OH− and is considered a *strong base*.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Nitric acid, with a p*K* value of around −1.7, behaves as a strong acid in aqueous solutions with a pH greater than 1.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At lower pH values it behaves as a weak acid.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*K*a values for strong acids have been estimated by theoretical means.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the p*K*a value of aqueous HCl has been estimated as −9.3.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is the Henderson–Hasselbalch equation, from which the following conclusions can be drawn.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In water, measurable p*K*a values range from about −2 for a strong acid to about 12 for a very weak acid (or strong base).
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A buffer solution of a desired pH can be prepared as a mixture of a weak acid and its conjugate base.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In practice, the mixture can be created by dissolving the acid in water, and adding the requisite amount of strong acid or base.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the p*K*a and analytical concentration of the acid are known, the extent of dissociation and pH of a solution of a monoprotic acid can be easily calculated using an ICE table.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A polyprotic acid is a compound which may lose more than 1 proton.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Stepwise dissociation constants are each defined for the loss of a single proton.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The constant for dissociation of the first proton may be denoted as *K*a1 and the constants for dissociation of successive protons as *K*a2, etc.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Phosphoric acid, H3PO4, is an example of a polyprotic acid as it can lose three protons.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The species distribution diagram shows that the concentrations of the two ions are maximum at pH 5.5 and 10.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the difference between successive p*K* values is less than about four there is overlap between the pH range of existence of the species in equilibrium.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The smaller the difference, the more the overlap.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The case of citric acid is shown at the right; solutions of citric acid are buffered over the whole range of pH 2.5 to 7.5.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] According to Pauling's first rule, successive p*K* values of a given acid increase (p*K*a2 > p*K*a1).
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For oxyacids with more than one ionizable hydrogen on the same atom, the p*K*a values often increase by about 5 units for each proton removed, as in the example of phosphoric acid above.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It can be seen in the table above that the second proton is removed from a negatively charged species.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Since the proton carries a positive charge extra work is needed to remove it, which is why p*K*a2 is greater than p*K*a1. p*K*a3 is greater than p*K*a2 because there is further charge separation.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When an exception to Pauling's rule is found, it indicates that a major change in structure is also occurring.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the case of VO+2(aq), the vanadium is octahedral, 6-coordinate, whereas vanadic acid is tetrahedral, 4-coordinate.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This means that four "particles" are released with the first dissociation, but only two "particles" are released with the other dissociations, resulting in a much greater entropy contribution to the standard Gibbs free energy change for the first reaction than for the others.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For substances in solution, the isoelectric point (p*I*) is defined as the pH at which the sum, weighted by charge value, of concentrations of positively charged species is equal to the weighted sum of concentrations of negatively charged species.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the case that there is one species of each type, the isoelectric point can be obtained directly from the p*K* values.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Take the example of glycine, defined as AH.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] There are two dissociation equilibria to consider.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*I* values for amino acids are listed at proteinogenic amino acid.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When more than two charged species are in equilibrium with each other a full speciation calculation may be needed.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When *K*a, *K*b and *K*w are determined under the same conditions of temperature and ionic strength, it follows, taking cologarithms, that p*K*b = p*K*w − p*K*a.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] with sufficient accuracy for most practical purposes.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In effect there is no need to define p*K*b separately from p*K*a, but it is done here as often only p*K*b values can be found in the older literature.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is the reciprocal of an association constant for formation of the complex.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Because the relationship p*K*b = p*K*w − p*K*a holds only in aqueous solutions (though analogous relationships apply for other amphoteric solvents), subdisciplines of chemistry like organic chemistry that usually deal with nonaqueous solutions generally do not use p*K*b as a measure of basicity.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Instead, the p*K*a of the conjugate acid, denoted by p*K*aH, is quoted when basicity needs to be quantified.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A higher value for p*K*aH corresponds to a stronger base.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the values p*K*aH (C5H5N) = 5.25 and p*K*aH ((CH3CH2)3N) = 10.75 indicate that (CH3CH2)3N (triethylamine) is a stronger base than C5H5N (pyridine).
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An amphoteric substance is one that can act as an acid or as a base, depending on pH.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Carbonic acid equilibria are important for acid–base homeostasis in the human body.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An amino acid is also amphoteric with the added complication that the neutral molecule is subject to an internal acid–base equilibrium in which the basic amino group attracts and binds the proton from the acidic carboxyl group, forming a zwitterion.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At pH less than about 5 both the carboxylate group and the amino group are protonated.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At high pH a second dissociation may take place.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Thus the amino acid molecule is amphoteric because it may either be protonated or deprotonated.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The water molecule may either gain or lose a proton.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where in aqueous solution H+ denotes a solvated proton.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Often this is written as the hydronium ion H3O+, but this formula is not exact because in fact there is solvation by more than one water molecule and species such as H5O+2, H7O+3, and H9O+4 are also present.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The self-ionization constant of water, *K*w, is thus just a special case of an acid dissociation constant.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At that temperature both hydrogen and hydroxide ions have a concentration of 10−7 M.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a high donor number, making it a strong Lewis base.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a high dielectric constant (relative permittivity), making it a good solvent for ionic species.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*K*a values of organic compounds are often obtained using the aprotic solvents dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO) and acetonitrile (ACN).
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] DMSO is widely used as an alternative to water because it has a lower dielectric constant than water, and is less polar and so dissolves non-polar, hydrophobic substances more easily.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a measurable p*K*a range of about 1 to 30.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acetonitrile is less basic than DMSO, and, so, in general, acids are weaker and bases are stronger in this solvent.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Some p*K*a values at 25 °C for acetonitrile (ACN) and dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO). are shown in the following tables.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Values for water are included for comparison.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ionization of acids is less in an acidic solvent than in water.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, hydrogen chloride is a weak acid when dissolved in acetic acid.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is because acetic acid is a much weaker base than water.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The unlikely geminal diol species CH3C(OH)+2 is stable in these environments.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For aqueous solutions the pH scale is the most convenient acidity function.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other acidity functions have been proposed for non-aqueous media, the most notable being the Hammett acidity function, *H*0, for superacid media and its modified version *H*− for superbasic media.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aprotic solvents, oligomers, such as the well-known acetic acid dimer, may be formed by hydrogen bonding.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid may also form hydrogen bonds to its conjugate base.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This process, known as homoconjugation, has the effect of enhancing the acidity of acids, lowering their effective p*K*a values, by stabilizing the conjugate base.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Homoconjugation enhances the proton-donating power of toluenesulfonic acid in acetonitrile solution by a factor of nearly 800.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aqueous solutions, homoconjugation does not occur, because water forms stronger hydrogen bonds to the conjugate base than does the acid.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When a compound has limited solubility in water it is common practice (in the pharmaceutical industry, for example) to determine p*K*a values in a solvent mixture such as water/dioxane or water/methanol, in which the compound is more soluble.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the example shown at the right, the p*K*a value rises steeply with increasing percentage of dioxane as the dielectric constant of the mixture is decreasing.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A p*K*a value obtained in a mixed solvent cannot be used directly for aqueous solutions.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The reason for this is that when the solvent is in its standard state its activity is *defined* as one.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the standard state of water:dioxane mixture with 9:1 mixing ratio is precisely that solvent mixture, with no added solutes.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To obtain the p*K*a value for use with aqueous solutions it has to be extrapolated to zero co-solvent concentration from values obtained from various co-solvent mixtures.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These facts are obscured by the omission of the solvent from the expression that is normally used to define p*K*a, but p*K*a values obtained in a *given* mixed solvent can be compared to each other, giving relative acid strengths.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The same is true of p*K*a values obtained in a particular non-aqueous solvent such a DMSO.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A universal, solvent-independent, scale for acid dissociation constants has not been developed, since there is no known way to compare the standard states of two different solvents.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Pauling's second rule is that the value of the first p*K*a for acids of the formula XO*m*(OH)*n* depends primarily on the number of oxo groups *m*, and is approximately independent of the number of hydroxy groups *n*, and also of the central atom X.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Alternatively, various numerical formulas have been proposed including p*K*a = 8 − 5*m* (known as Bell's rule), p*K*a = 7 − 5*m*, or p*K*a = 9 − 7*m*.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The dependence on *m* correlates with the oxidation state of the central atom, X: the higher the oxidation state the stronger the oxyacid.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, p*K*a for HClO is 7.2, for HClO2 is 2.0, for HClO3 is −1 and HClO4 is a strong acid (p*K*a ≪ 0).
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The increased acidity on adding an oxo group is due to stabilization of the conjugate base by delocalization of its negative charge over an additional oxygen atom.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This rule can help assign molecular structure: for example, phosphorous acid, having molecular formula H3PO3, has a p*K*a near 2, which suggested that the structure is HPO(OH)2, as later confirmed by NMR spectroscopy, and not P(OH)3, which would be expected to have a p*K*a near 8.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Inductive effects and mesomeric effects affect the p*K*a values.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A simple example is provided by the effect of replacing the hydrogen atoms in acetic acid by the more electronegative chlorine atom.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The electron-withdrawing effect of the substituent makes ionisation easier, so successive p*K*a values decrease in the series 4.7, 2.8, 1.4, and 0.7 when 0, 1, 2, or 3 chlorine atoms are present.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The Hammett equation, provides a general expression for the effect of substituents.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Alcohols do not normally behave as acids in water, but the presence of a double bond adjacent to the OH group can substantially decrease the p*K*a by the mechanism of keto–enol tautomerism.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ascorbic acid is an example of this effect.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The diketone 2,4-pentanedione (acetylacetone) is also a weak acid because of the keto–enol equilibrium.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aromatic compounds, such as phenol, which have an OH substituent, conjugation with the aromatic ring as a whole greatly increases the stability of the deprotonated form.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Structural effects can also be important.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The difference between fumaric acid and maleic acid is a classic example.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Fumaric acid is (E)-1,4-but-2-enedioic acid, a *trans* isomer, whereas maleic acid is the corresponding *cis* isomer, i.e.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] (Z)-1,4-but-2-enedioic acid (see cis-trans isomerism).
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Fumaric acid has p*K*a values of approximately 3.0 and 4.5.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] By contrast, maleic acid has p*K*a values of approximately 1.5 and 6.5.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The reason for this large difference is that when one proton is removed from the *cis* isomer (maleic acid) a strong intramolecular hydrogen bond is formed with the nearby remaining carboxyl group.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This favors the formation of the maleate H+, and it opposes the removal of the second proton from that species.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the *trans* isomer, the two carboxyl groups are always far apart, so hydrogen bonding is not observed.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Proton sponge, 1,8-bis(dimethylamino)naphthalene, has a p*K*a value of 12.1.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is one of the strongest amine bases known.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The high basicity is attributed to the relief of strain upon protonation and strong internal hydrogen bonding.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Effects of the solvent and solvation should be mentioned also in this section.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It turns out, these influences are more subtle than that of a dielectric medium mentioned above.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the expected (by electronic effects of methyl substituents) and observed in gas phase order of basicity of methylamines, Me3N > Me2NH > MeNH2 > NH3, is changed by water to Me2NH > MeNH2 > Me3N > NH3.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Neutral methylamine molecules are hydrogen-bonded to water molecules mainly through one acceptor, N–HOH, interaction and only occasionally just one more donor bond, NH–OH2.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Hence, methylamines are stabilized to about the same extent by hydration, regardless of the number of methyl groups.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In stark contrast, corresponding methylammonium cations always utilize **all** the available protons for donor NH–OH2 bonding.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Relative stabilization of methylammonium ions thus decreases with the number of methyl groups explaining the order of water basicity of methylamines.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The standard enthalpy change can be determined by calorimetry or by using the van 't Hoff equation, though the calorimetric method is preferable.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When both the standard enthalpy change and acid dissociation constant have been determined, the standard entropy change is easily calculated from the equation above.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the following table, the entropy terms are calculated from the experimental values of p*K*a and Δ*H*⊖.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The data were critically selected and refer to 25 °C and zero ionic strength, in water.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The first point to note is that, when p*K*a is positive, the standard free energy change for the dissociation reaction is also positive.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Second, some reactions are exothermic and some are endothermic, but, when Δ*H*⊖ is negative *T*ΔS⊖ is the dominant factor, which determines that Δ*G*⊖ is positive.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Last, the entropy contribution is always unfavourable (Δ*S*⊖ < 0) in these reactions.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ions in aqueous solution tend to orient the surrounding water molecules, which orders the solution and decreases the entropy.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The contribution of an ion to the entropy is the partial molar entropy which is often negative, especially for small or highly charged ions.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The ionization of a neutral acid involves formation of two ions so that the entropy decreases (Δ*S*⊖ < 0).
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] On the second ionization of the same acid, there are now three ions and the anion has a charge, so the entropy again decreases.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note that the *standard* free energy change for the reaction is for the changes *from* the reactants in their standard states *to* the products in their standard states.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The free energy change *at* equilibrium is zero since the chemical potentials of reactants and products are equal at equilibrium.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The experimental determination of p*K*a values is commonly performed by means of titrations, in a medium of high ionic strength and at constant temperature.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A typical procedure would be as follows.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A solution of the compound in the medium is acidified with a strong acid to the point where the compound is fully protonated.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The solution is then titrated with a strong base until all the protons have been removed.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At each point in the titration pH is measured using a glass electrode and a pH meter.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The equilibrium constants are found by fitting calculated pH values to the observed values, using the method of least squares.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The total volume of added strong base should be small compared to the initial volume of titrand solution in order to keep the ionic strength nearly constant.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This will ensure that p*K*a remains invariant during the titration.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A calculated titration curve for oxalic acid is shown at the right.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Oxalic acid has p*K*a values of 1.27 and 4.27.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Therefore, the buffer regions will be centered at about pH 1.3 and pH 4.3.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The buffer regions carry the information necessary to get the p*K*a values as the concentrations of acid and conjugate base change along a buffer region.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Between the two buffer regions there is an end-point, or equivalence point, at about pH 3.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This end-point is not sharp and is typical of a diprotic acid whose buffer regions overlap by a small amount: p*K*a2 − p*K*a1 is about three in this example.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] (If the difference in p*K* values were about two or less, the end-point would not be noticeable.) The second end-point begins at about pH 6.3 and is sharp.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This indicates that all the protons have been removed.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When this is so, the solution is not buffered and the pH rises steeply on addition of a small amount of strong base.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] However, the pH does not continue to rise indefinitely.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A new buffer region begins at about pH 11 (p*K*w − 3), which is where self-ionization of water becomes important.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is very difficult to measure pH values of less than two in aqueous solution with a glass electrode, because the Nernst equation breaks down at such low pH values.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To determine p*K* values of less than about 2 or more than about 11 spectrophotometric or NMR measurements may be used instead of, or combined with, pH measurements.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the glass electrode cannot be employed, as with non-aqueous solutions, spectrophotometric methods are frequently used.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These may involve absorbance or fluorescence measurements.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In both cases the measured quantity is assumed to be proportional to the sum of contributions from each photo-active species; with absorbance measurements the Beer–Lambert law is assumed to apply.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Isothermal titration calorimetry (ITC) may be used to determine both a p*K* value and the corresponding standard enthalpy for acid dissociation.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Software to perform the calculations is supplied by the instrument manufacturers for simple systems.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Aqueous solutions with normal water cannot be used for 1H NMR measurements but heavy water, D2O, must be used instead.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] 13C NMR data, however, can be used with normal water and 1H NMR spectra can be used with non-aqueous media.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The quantities measured with NMR are time-averaged chemical shifts, as proton exchange is fast on the NMR time-scale.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other chemical shifts, such as those of 31P can be measured.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For some polyprotic acids, dissociation (or association) occurs at more than one nonequivalent site, and the observed macroscopic equilibrium constant, or macro-constant, is a combination of micro-constants involving distinct species.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When one reactant forms two products in parallel, the macro-constant is a sum of two micro-constants, $K=K_{X}+K_{Y}.$ This is true for example for the deprotonation of the amino acid cysteine, which exists in solution as a neutral zwitterion HS−CH2−CH(NH+3)−COO−.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Similarly, a base such as spermine has more than one site where protonation can occur.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, mono-protonation can occur at a terminal −NH2 group or at internal −NH− groups.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The *K*b values for dissociation of spermine protonated at one or other of the sites are examples of micro-constants.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] They cannot be determined directly by means of pH, absorbance, fluorescence or NMR measurements; a measured *K*b value is the sum of the K values for the micro-reactions.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Nevertheless, the site of protonation is very important for biological function, so mathematical methods have been developed for the determination of micro-constants.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When a reactant undergoes two reactions in series, the macro-constant for the combined reaction is the product of the micro-constant for the two steps.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A knowledge of p*K*a values is important for the quantitative treatment of systems involving acid–base equilibria in solution.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Many applications exist in biochemistry; for example, the p*K*a values of proteins and amino acid side chains are of major importance for the activity of enzymes and the stability of proteins.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Protein p*K*a values cannot always be measured directly, but may be calculated using theoretical methods.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffer solutions are used extensively to provide solutions at or near the physiological pH for the study of biochemical reactions; the design of these solutions depends on a knowledge of the p*K*a values of their components.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Important buffer solutions include MOPS, which provides a solution with pH 7.2, and tricine, which is used in gel electrophoresis.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffering is an essential part of acid base physiology including acid–base homeostasis, and is key to understanding disorders such as acid–base disorder.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The isoelectric point of a given molecule is a function of its p*K* values, so different molecules have different isoelectric points.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This permits a technique called isoelectric focusing, which is used for separation of proteins by 2-D gel polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffer solutions also play a key role in analytical chemistry.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] They are used whenever there is a need to fix the pH of a solution at a particular value.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Compared with an aqueous solution, the pH of a buffer solution is relatively insensitive to the addition of a small amount of strong acid or strong base.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The buffer capacity of a simple buffer solution is largest when pH = p*K*a.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In acid–base extraction, the efficiency of extraction of a compound into an organic phase, such as an ether, can be optimised by adjusting the pH of the aqueous phase using an appropriate buffer.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] At the optimum pH, the concentration of the electrically neutral species is maximised; such a species is more soluble in organic solvents having a low dielectric constant than it is in water.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This technique is used for the purification of weak acids and bases.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A pH indicator is a weak acid or weak base that changes colour in the transition pH range, which is approximately p*K*a ± 1.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The design of a universal indicator requires a mixture of indicators whose adjacent p*K*a values differ by about two, so that their transition pH ranges just overlap.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In pharmacology, ionization of a compound alters its physical behaviour and macro properties such as solubility and lipophilicity, log *p*).
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] For example, ionization of any compound will increase the solubility in water, but decrease the lipophilicity.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This is exploited in drug development to increase the concentration of a compound in the blood by adjusting the p*K*a of an ionizable group.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Knowledge of p*K*a values is important for the understanding of coordination complexes, which are formed by the interaction of a metal ion, Mm+, acting as a Lewis acid, with a ligand, L, acting as a Lewis base.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] To determine the equilibrium constant for this reaction, in which the ligand loses a proton, the p*K*a of the protonated ligand must be known.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In practice, the ligand may be polyprotic; for example EDTA4− can accept four protons; in that case, all p*K*a values must be known.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In addition, the metal ion is subject to hydrolysis, that is, it behaves as a weak acid, so the p*K* values for the hydrolysis reactions must also be known.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Assessing the hazard associated with an acid or base may require a knowledge of p*K*a values.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] For example, hydrogen cyanide is a very toxic gas, because the cyanide ion inhibits the iron-containing enzyme cytochrome c oxidase.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Hydrogen cyanide is a weak acid in aqueous solution with a p*K*a of about 9.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In strongly alkaline solutions, above pH 11, say, it follows that sodium cyanide is "fully dissociated" so the hazard due to the hydrogen cyanide gas is much reduced.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] An acidic solution, on the other hand, is very hazardous because all the cyanide is in its acid form.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Ingestion of cyanide by mouth is potentially fatal, independently of pH, because of the reaction with cytochrome c oxidase.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In environmental science acid–base equilibria are important for lakes and rivers; for example, humic acids are important components of natural waters.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] There are multiple techniques to determine the p*K*a of a chemical, leading to some discrepancies between different sources.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Well measured values are typically within 0.1 units of each other.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Data presented here were taken at 25 °C in water.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] More values can be found in the Thermodynamics section, above.
[src:selenocysteine/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A table of p*K*a of carbon acids, measured in DMSO, can be found on the page on carbanions.
[src:selenocysteine/alanine] Under biological conditions, alanine exists in its zwitterionic form with its amine group protonated (as −NH+3) and its carboxyl group deprotonated (as −CO−2).
[src:selenocysteine/alanine] Alanine is encoded by all codons starting with GC (GCU, GCC, GCA, and GCG).
[src:selenocysteine/alanine] The L-isomer of alanine (left-handed) is the one that is incorporated into proteins.
[src:selenocysteine/alanine] L-alanine is second only to L-leucine in rate of occurrence, accounting for 7.8% of the primary structure in a sample of 1,150 proteins.
[src:selenocysteine/alanine] The right-handed form, D-alanine, occurs in peptides in some bacterial cell walls (in peptidoglycan) and in some peptide antibiotics, and occurs in the tissues of many crustaceans and molluscs as an osmolyte.
[src:selenocysteine/alanine] Alanine is not an essential amino acid in humans because it can be synthesized metabolically and does not need to be present in the diet.
[src:selenocysteine/alanine] However hypoalaninemia (alanine deficiency) is possible under certain conditions such as ketotic hypoglycemia.
[src:selenocysteine/alanine] Alanine was first synthesized in 1850 when Adolph Strecker combined acetaldehyde and ammonia with hydrogen cyanide.
[src:selenocysteine/alanine] The amino acid was named *Alanin* in German, in reference to aldehyde, with the interfix *-an-* for ease of pronunciation, the German ending *-in* used in chemical compounds being analogous to English *-ine*.
[src:selenocysteine/alanine] Alanine is an aliphatic amino acid, because the side-chain connected to the α-carbon atom is a methyl group (-CH3).
[src:selenocysteine/alanine] Alanine is the simplest α-amino acid after glycine.
[src:selenocysteine/alanine] The methyl side-chain of alanine is non-reactive and is therefore hardly ever directly involved in protein function.
[src:selenocysteine/alanine] Alanine is a nonessential amino acid, meaning it can be manufactured by the human body, and does not need to be obtained through the diet.
[src:selenocysteine/alanine] Alanine is found in a wide variety of foods, but is particularly concentrated in meats.
[src:selenocysteine/aliphatic-compound] In organic chemistry, hydrocarbons (compounds composed solely of carbon and hydrogen) are divided into two classes: aromatic compounds and **aliphatic compounds** (/ˌælɪˈfætɪk/; G.
[src:selenocysteine/aliphatic-compound] Aliphatic compounds can be saturated (in which all the C-C bonds are single, requiring the structure to be completed, or 'saturated', by hydrogen) like hexane, or unsaturated, like hexene and hexyne.
[src:selenocysteine/aliphatic-compound] Open-chain compounds, whether straight or branched, and which contain no rings of any type, are always aliphatic.
[src:selenocysteine/aliphatic-compound] Cyclic compounds can be aliphatic if they are not aromatic.
[src:selenocysteine/aliphatic-compound] Aliphatic compounds can be saturated, joined by single bonds (alkanes), or unsaturated, with double bonds (alkenes) or triple bonds (alkynes).
[src:selenocysteine/aliphatic-compound] If other elements (heteroatoms) are bound to the carbon chain, the most common being oxygen, nitrogen, sulfur, and chlorine, it is no longer a hydrocarbon, and therefore no longer an aliphatic compound.
[src:selenocysteine/aliphatic-compound] However, such compounds may still be referred to as aliphatic if the hydrocarbon portion of the molecule is aliphatic, e.g. aliphatic amines, to differentiate them from aromatic amines.
[src:selenocysteine/aliphatic-compound] The least complex aliphatic compound is methane (CH4).
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Carl Linnaeus first described the genus *Allium* in 1753.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The generic name *Allium* is the Latin word for garlic, and the type species for the genus is *Allium sativum* which means "cultivated garlic".
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The decision to include a species in the genus *Allium* is taxonomically difficult, and species boundaries are unclear.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Estimates of the number of species are as low as 260, and as high as 979.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] In the APG III classification system, *Allium* is placed in the family Amaryllidaceae, subfamily Allioideae (formerly the family Alliaceae).
[src:selenocysteine/allium] In some of the older classification systems, *Allium* was placed in Liliaceae.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Molecular phylogenetic studies have shown this circumscription of Liliaceae is not monophyletic.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Various *Allium* species have been cultivated from the earliest times.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] About a dozen species are economically important as crops, or garden vegetables, and an increasing number of species are important as ornamental plants.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Plants belonging to this genus produce cysteine-derived organosulfur compounds, which impart a distinctive onion or garlic flavor and scent.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Many are used as food plants, though not all members of the genus are equally flavorful.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] In most cases, both bulb and leaves are edible.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The characteristic *Allium* flavor depends on the sulfate content of the soil the plant grows in.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] In the rare occurrence of sulfur-depleted growth conditions, all *Allium* species completely lose their usual odors and flavors.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The genus *Allium* (alliums) is characterised by herbaceous geophyte perennials with true bulbs, some of which are borne on rhizomes, and an onion or garlic odor and flavor.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The bulbs are solitary or clustered and tunicate and the plants are perennialized by the bulbs reforming annually from the base of the old bulbs, or are produced on the ends of rhizomes or, in a few species, at the ends of stolons.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] A small number of species have tuberous roots.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The bulbs' outer coats are commonly brown or grey, with a smooth texture, and are fibrous, or with cellular reticulation.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The inner coats of the bulbs are membranous.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Many alliums have basal leaves that commonly wither away from the tips downward before or while the plants flower, but some species have persistent foliage.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Plants produce from one to 12 leaves, most species having linear, channeled or flat leaf blades.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The leaf blades are straight or variously coiled, but some species have broad leaves, including *A. victorialis* and *A. tricoccum*.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The leaves are sessile, and very rarely narrowed into a petiole.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The flowers, which are produced on scapes are erect or in some species pendent, having six petal-like tepals produced in two whorls.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The flowers have one style and six epipetalous stamens; the anthers and pollen can vary in color depending on the species.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The ovaries are superior, and three-lobed with three locules.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The fruits are capsules that open longitudinally along the capsule wall between the partitions of the locule.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The seeds are black, and have a rounded shape.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The terete or flattened flowering scapes are normally persistent.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The inflorescences are umbels, in which the outside flowers bloom first and flowering progresses to the inside.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Some species produce bulbils within the umbels, and in some species, such as *Allium paradoxum*, the bulbils replace some or all the flowers.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The umbels are subtended by noticeable spathe bracts, which are commonly fused and normally have around three veins.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Some bulbous alliums increase by forming little bulbs or "offsets" around the old one, as well as by seed.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Several species can form many bulbils in the flowerhead; in the so-called "tree onion" or Egyptian onion (*A.* × *proliferum*) the bulbils are few, but large enough to be pickled.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Many of the species of *Allium* have been used as food items throughout their ranges.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] There are several unrelated species that are somewhat similar in appearance to alliums but are poisonous (e.g. in North America, death camas, *Toxicoscordion venenosum*), but none of these has the distinctive scent of onions or garlic.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] With over 850 to 1,000 species *Allium* is the sole genus in the Allieae, one of four tribes of subfamily Allioideae (Amaryllidaceae).
[src:selenocysteine/allium] New species continue to be described and *Allium* is one of the largest monocotyledonous genera, but the precise taxonomy of *Allium* is poorly understood, with incorrect descriptions being widespread.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The difficulties arise from the fact that the genus displays considerable polymorphism and has adapted to a wide variety of habitats.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Furthermore, traditional classifications had been based on homoplasious characteristics (the independent evolution of similar features in species of different lineages).
[src:selenocysteine/allium] However, the genus has been shown to be monophyletic, containing three major clades, although some proposed subgenera are not.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Some progress is being made using molecular phylogenetic methods, and the internal transcribed spacer (ITS) region, including the 5.8S rDNA and the two spacers ITS1 and ITS2, is one of the more commonly used markers in the study of the differentiation of the *Allium* species.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] When Linnaeus formerly described the genus *Allium* in his *Species Plantarum* (1753), there were thirty species with this name.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] He placed *Allium* in a grouping he referred to as *Hexandria monogynia* (i.e. six stamens and one pistil) containing 51 genera in all.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Linnaeus originally grouped his 30 species into three alliances, e.g.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Since then, many attempts have been made to divide the growing number of recognised species into infrageneric subgroupings, initially as sections, and then as subgenera further divided into sections.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The modern era of phylogenetic analysis dates to 1996.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] In 2006 Friesen, Fritsch, and Blattner described a new classification with 15 subgenera, 56 sections, and about 780 species based on the nuclear ribosomal gene internal transcribed spacers.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Some of the subgenera correspond to the once separate genera (*Caloscordum*, *Milula*, *Nectaroscordum*) included in the Gilliesieae.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The terminology has varied with some authors subdividing subgenera into Sections and others Alliances.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The term Alliance has also been used for subgroupings within species, e.g.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Subsequent molecular phylogenetic studies have shown the 2006 classification is a considerable improvement over previous classifications, but some of its subgenera and sections are probably not monophyletic.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Meanwhile, the number of new species continued to increase, reaching 800 by 2009, and the pace of discovery has not decreased.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Detailed studies have focused on a number of subgenera, including *Amerallium*.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] *Amerallium* is strongly supported as monophyletic.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Subgenus *Melanocrommyum* has also been the subject of considerable study , while work on subgenus *Allium* has focussed on section *Allium*, including *Allium ampeloprasum*, although sampling was not sufficient to test the monophyly of the section.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The major evolutionary lineages or lines correspond to the three major clades.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Line one (the oldest) with three subgenera is predominantly bulbous, the second, with five subgenera and the third with seven subgenera contain both bulbous and rhizomatous taxa.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The three evolutionary lineages and 15 subgenera here represent the classification schemes of Friesen et al.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] (2006) and Li (2010), and subsequent additional species and revisions.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Although this lineage consists of three subgenera, nearly all the species are attributed to subgenus *Amerallium*, the third largest subgenus of *Allium*.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The lineage is considered to represent the most ancient line within *Allium*, and to be the only lineage that is purely bulbous, the other two having both bulbous and rhizomatous taxa.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Within the lineage *Amerallium* is a sister group to the other two subgenera (*Microscordum*+*Nectaroscordum*).
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Nearly all the species in this lineage of five subgenera are accounted for by subgenus *Melanocrommyum*, which is most closely associated with subgenera *Vvedenskya* and *Porphyroprason*, phylogenetically.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] These three genera are late-branching whereas the remaining two subgenera, *Caloscordum* and *Anguinum*, are early branching.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The third evolutionary line contains the greatest number of sections (seven), and also the largest subgenus of the genus *Allium*: subgenus *Allium*, which includes the type species of the genus, *Allium sativum*.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] This subgenus also contains the majority of the species in its lineage.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Within the lineage, the phylogeny is complex.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Two small subgenera, *Butomissa* and *Cyathophora* form a sister clade to the remaining five subgenera, with *Butomissa* as the first branching group.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Amongst the remaining five subgenera, *Rhizirideum* forms a medium-sized subgenus that is the sister to the other four, larger, subgenera.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The majority of *Allium* species are native to the Northern Hemisphere, being spread throughout the holarctic region, from dry subtropics to the boreal zone, predominantly in Asia.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Of the latter, 138 species occur in China, about a sixth of all *Allium* species, representing five subgenera.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] A few species are native to Africa and Central and South America.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] A single known exception, *Allium dregeanum* occurs in the Southern Hemisphere (South Africa).
[src:selenocysteine/allium] There are two centres of diversity, a major one from the Mediterranean Basin to Central Asia and Pakistan, while a minor one is found in western North America.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The genus is especially diverse in the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Species grow in various conditions from dry, well-drained mineral-based soils to moist, organic soils; most grow in sunny locations, but a number also grow in forests (e.g., *A. ursinum*), or even in swamps or water.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The genus *Allium* has very large variation between species in their genome size that is not accompanied by changes in ploidy level.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] This remarkable variation was noted in the discussion of the evolution of junk DNA and resulted in the Onion Test, a "reality check for anyone who thinks they have come up with a universal function for junk DNA".
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Genome sizes vary between 7.5 Gb in *A. schoenoprasum* and 30.9 Gb in *A. ursinum*, both of which are diploid.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Many *Allium* species have been harvested through human history, but only about a dozen are still economically important today as crops or garden vegetables.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Many *Allium* species and hybrids are cultivated as ornamentals.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] These include *A. cristophii* and *A. giganteum*, which are used as border plants for their ornamental flowers, and their "architectural" qualities.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Several hybrids have been bred, or selected, with rich purple flowers.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] *A. hollandicum* 'Purple Sensation' is one of the most popular and has been given an Award of Garden Merit (H4).
[src:selenocysteine/allium] These ornamental onions produce spherical umbels on single stalks in spring and summer, in a wide variety of sizes and colours, ranging from white (*Allium* 'Mont Blanc'), blue (*A. caeruleum*), to yellow (*A. flavum*) and purple (*A. giganteum*).
[src:selenocysteine/allium] By contrast, other species (such as invasive *A. triquetrum* and *A. ursinum*) can become troublesome garden weeds.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Dogs and cats are very susceptible to poisoning after the consumption of certain species.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Cattle have occasionally suffered onion toxicosis as well.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Vegetables of the *Allium* genus can cause digestive disorders for human beings.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] The genus includes many economically important species.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] These include onions (*A. cepa*), French shallots (*A. oschaninii*), leeks (*A. ampeloprasum*), garlic (*A. sativum*), and herbs such as scallions (various *Allium* species) and chives (*A. schoenoprasum*).
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Some have been used as traditional medicines.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] Members of the genus and plants with similar properties, referred to in this context as 'leeks', had a prominent role in Germanic paganism.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] This includes writing the word *laukaz* ('leek') in runic inscriptions, likely for protection and healing.
[src:selenocysteine/allium] This genus also includes species that are abundantly gathered from the wild such as wild garlic (*Allium ursinum*) in Europe and ramps (*Allium tricoccum*) in North America.
[src:selenocysteine/aluminium-selenide] The pure compound is white, but typical samples are coloured.
[src:selenocysteine/aluminium-selenide] Al2Se3 has been used as a precursor to hydrogen selenide, which is released when the solid is treated with acids.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Selenocysteine is present in several enzymes (for example glutathione peroxidases, tetraiodothyronine 5′ deiodinases, thioredoxin reductases, formate dehydrogenases, glycine reductases, selenophosphate synthetase 2, methionine-*R*-sulfoxide reductase B1 (SEPX1), and some hydrogenases).
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] It occurs in all three domains of life, including important enzymes (listed above) present in humans.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Selenocysteine was discovered in 1974 by biochemist Thressa Stadtman at the National Institutes of Health.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Selenocysteine is the Se-analogue of cysteine.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] It is rarely encountered outside of living tissue (nor is it available commercially) because of its high susceptiblility to air-oxidation.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] More common is the oxidized derivative selenocystine, which has an Se-Se bond.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Both selenocysteine and selenocystine are white solids.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] The Se-H group is more acidic (p*K*a = 5.43) than the thiol group; thus, it is deprotonated at physiological pH.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Selenocysteine has the same structure as cysteine, but with an atom of selenium taking the place of the usual sulfur; it has a selenol group.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Like other natural proteinogenic amino acids, cysteine and selenocysteine have L chirality in the older D/L notation based on homology to D- and L-glyceraldehyde.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] In the newer *R*/*S* system of designating chirality, based on the atomic numbers of atoms near the asymmetric carbon, they have *R* chirality, because of the presence of sulfur or selenium as a second neighbor to the asymmetric carbon.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Proteins which contain a selenocysteine residue are called selenoproteins.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Most selenoproteins contain a single selenocysteine residue.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Selenoproteins that exhibit catalytic activity are called selenoenzymes.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Unlike the other amino acids, no free pool of selenocysteine exists in the cell.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Its high reactivity would cause damage to cells.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Instead, cells store selenium in the less reactive oxidized form, selenocystine, or in methylated form, selenomethionine.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Selenocysteine synthesis occurs on a specialized tRNA, which also functions to incorporate it into nascent polypeptides.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] The selenocysteine tRNAs are initially charged with serine by seryl-tRNA ligase, but the resulting Ser-tRNASec is not used for translation because it is not recognised by the normal translation elongation factor (EF-Tu in bacteria, eEF1A in eukaryotes).
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Rather, the tRNA-bound seryl residue is converted to a selenocysteine residue by the pyridoxal phosphate-containing enzyme selenocysteine synthase.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] In eukaryotes and archaea, two enzymes are required to convert tRNA-bound seryl residue into tRNA selenocysteinyl residue: PSTK (*O*-phosphoseryl-tRNA[Ser]Sec kinase) and selenocysteine synthase.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Finally, the resulting Sec-tRNASecis specifically bound to an alternative translational elongation factor (SelB or mSelB (or eEFSec)), which delivers it in a targeted manner to the ribosomes translating mRNAs for selenoproteins.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] The specificity of this delivery mechanism is brought about by the presence of an extra protein domain (in bacteria, SelB) or an extra subunit (SBP2 for eukaryotic mSelB/eEFSec) which bind to the corresponding RNA secondary structures formed by the SECIS elements in selenoprotein mRNAs.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Selenocysteine has a lower reduction potential than cysteine.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] These properties make it very suitable in proteins that are involved in antioxidant activity.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Although it is found in the three domains of life, it is not universal in all organisms.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Unlike other amino acids present in biological proteins, selenocysteine is not coded for directly in the genetic code.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Instead, it is encoded in a special way by a UGA codon, which is normally the "opal" stop codon.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Such a mechanism is called translational recoding and its efficiency depends on the selenoprotein being synthesized and on translation initiation factors.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] When cells are grown in the absence of selenium, translation of selenoproteins terminates at the UGA codon, resulting in a truncated, nonfunctional enzyme.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] The UGA codon is made to encode selenocysteine by the presence of a selenocysteine insertion sequence (SECIS) in the mRNA.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] The SECIS element is defined by characteristic nucleotide sequences and secondary structure base-pairing patterns.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] In bacteria, the SECIS element is typically located immediately following the UGA codon within the reading frame for the selenoprotein.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] In Archaea and in eukaryotes, the SECIS element is in the 3′ untranslated region (3′ UTR) of the mRNA and can direct multiple UGA codons to encode selenocysteine residues.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] As of 2021, 136 human proteins (in 37 families) are known to contain selenocysteine (selenoproteins).
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Selenocysteine is decomposed by the enzyme selenocysteine lyase into L-alanine and selenide.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] This probably helps with the safe recycling of Sec during degradation of selenoproteins.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Just as selenomethionine can be randomly incorporated into proteins, selenocystine can also be mistakenly attached to tRNACys by cysteinyl-tRNA synthetase and incorporated into proteins in lieu of cystine.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] A variant synthase that can distinguish between Cys and Sec helps reduce toxicity.
[src:selenocysteine/selenocysteine] Selenocysteine derivatives γ-glutamyl-*Se*-methylselenocysteine and *Se*-methylselenocysteine occur naturally in plants of the genera *Allium* and *Brassica*.
